{"actual_usd":0.125415,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":200,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24483,"reply":"\"I don't think you can knead those apart without ruining the loaf.\" *I rub a thumb through a dusting of flour on my apron and glance toward the bright square of the bakery window.* \"If Easter is only a symbol of new life, then it's a pretty one, but Christianity has staked an awful lot more than poetry on it. It requires that something actually happened — the tomb truly empty, Christ truly risen — or else the meaning comes loose from the world and starts calling itself faith when it's really just preference.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through.* \"Now, the symbol matters too. The new life, the hope, the whole of death being broken open — that's not garnish. But it rides on the fact. If the body stayed in the grave, then we're not talking about Christian faith in the old sturdy sense; we're talking about a moving idea. And an idea can't save you the way a living Lord can.\"","rolling_24h_usd":77.30994499999997,"run_id":"36bd5849-b90a-490c-8180-684d99a407cc"}
